article.headline: Gophers hand Hoosiers seventh straight loss
article.linkText: Whalen clutch down stretch to lead Gophers to win
article.story:
BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Lindsay Whalen was frustrated sitting
on the bench during the first half Sunday.

	   She made sure she took advantage of her second chance.

	   Whalen scored 27 points, including the last nine for her team,
as the (No. 16 ESPN/USA Today, No. 15 AP) Gophers overcame foul trouble and a strong Indiana defense for a 59-56 win.

	   "It was frustrating because I wanted to be able to help our
team,'' Whalen said. "(Assistant) Coach (Danielle) O'Banion said
this game is all about the second half.''

	   Whalen was too much for the Hoosiers (9-11, 2-8 Big Ten), who
lost their seventh straight and missed an opportunity to send the game into overtime at the buzzer.

	   She scored 10 of the Gophers' first 15 points before drawing her
second foul 11:17 into the game.

	   When she finally returned to start the second half, Whalen and
Janel McCarville, who missed the last six minutes of the first half
because of foul trouble, combined for 10 straight points to give
Minnesota a 37-31 lead. McCarville finished with 12 points and 14
rebounds, tying her season-high.

	   But when McCarville fouled out with 3:54 to go, the Gophers
looked for Whalen on every possession.

	   "I felt we played great as a team,'' Minnesota coach Pam Borton
said. "But Lindsay made the big plays at the end.''

	   The Gophers (17-4, 6-4) won their first conference road game of
the season, won at Indiana for the first time in three years and
won for only the second time in five games.

	   The Gophers entered the game with the nation's No. 2 scoring
offense at 82.3 points per game. But Whalen was the only Minnesota
player who looked like herself. She hit 10-of-17 from the field and
5-of-7 from the free-throw line.

	   But her teammates struggled, shooting 39.7 against the tough
Hoosiers defense.

	   "It was an outstanding defensive effort,'' Indiana coach Kathi
Bennett said. "We held them to 60 points, their field-goal
percentage was under 40. That was one of the better defensive
performances we've had.''

	   Indiana's problem, outside of Whalen, again was free-throw
shooting. Indiana went just 10 of 19 from the line.

	   "It's been addressed, and sometimes I think the more you talk
about it, the worse it gets,'' Bennett said. "When it's a
one-possession game, it hurts.''

	   Whalen's second-half performance hurt even more.

	   The Hoosiers grabbed a 53-52 lead when Kristen Bodine hit a
12-footer with 3:45 to play.

	   Then Whalen took over. She hit two free throws, stole a pass and
drove in for a layup to make it 56-53. With 23.2 seconds left,
Whalen beat Jill Hartman off the dribble for another layup and then
hit a free-throw with 10 seconds left for a 59-56 lead.

	   The Hoosiers tried to set a play for Hartman, who finished with
12 points and hit both of Indiana's 3-pointers, but the Gophers
defended her and forced Cindy Valentin, who led the Hoosiers with
15 points, to launch an errant 3 from the top of the key.

	   "To get back to playing free was nice,'' Whalen said. "I think
everybody's better when you're free. The more open you are, the
better the player you are.''
